SIMPLE: desiccate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Desiccate
<hw>Des"ic*cate</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Desiccated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Desiccating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>desiccatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>desiccare</ets> to dry up;
<ets>de-</ets> + <ets>siccare</ets> to dry, <ets>siccus</ets> dry. See
<er>Sack</er> wine.]</ety> <def>To dry up; to deprive or exhaust of
moisture; to preserve by drying; <as>as, to <ex>desiccate</ex> fish or
fruit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bodies <qex>desiccated</qex> by heat or age.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Desiccate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Desiccate
<hw>Des"ic*cate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become dry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Desiccation</ent>⟦br⟧
